1
00:00:02,133 --> 00:00:08,233
My topic is fixing Stable Diffusion
VAE's spurious bright pixels

2
00:00:08,633 --> 00:00:11,833
The core idea of this project is very simple

3
00:00:11,833 --> 00:00:14,700
To solve the tiny imperfections

4
00:00:14,700 --> 00:00:16,900
known as spurious bright pixels

5
00:00:16,900 --> 00:00:21,933
caused by VAEs when generating images using Stable Diffusion

6
00:00:24,366 --> 00:00:27,666
What are VAE's spurious bright pixels?

7
00:00:29,666 --> 00:00:32,866
When we generate images from Stable Diffusion

8
00:00:32,866 --> 00:00:36,433
we need VAE decoder to reconstruct

9
00:00:36,433 --> 00:00:40,933
the normal image from the latent image

10
00:00:42,200 --> 00:00:45,333
Because diffusion models generate

11
00:00:45,333 --> 00:00:49,333
latent images in a highly compressed dimension

12
00:00:50,566 --> 00:00:52,833
Lots of high-frequency detail

13
00:00:52,966 --> 00:00:56,133
can only be reconstructed

14
00:00:56,133 --> 00:01:01,333
by the distribution learned from the training data

15
00:01:02,666 --> 00:01:07,766
CFG is a parameter to control
how much the model

16
00:01:07,800 --> 00:01:10,200
follows the text prompt

17
00:01:11,166 --> 00:01:13,066
The higher the CFG

18
00:01:13,066 --> 00:01:18,700
the more the model influences

19
00:01:18,700 --> 00:01:24,633
the generation direction from the text prompt

20
00:01:25,600 --> 00:01:27,500
However the text prompt

21
00:01:27,500 --> 00:01:31,600
can only offer limited semantic information

22
00:01:32,233 --> 00:01:37,200
it lacks lots of detail or features
from the real image

23
00:01:39,166 --> 00:01:41,733
When CFG is too high

24
00:01:42,266 --> 00:01:45,400
the latent may be pulled
out of the distribution

25
00:01:45,433 --> 00:01:49,566
trained from the training data

26
00:01:51,733 --> 00:01:55,200
When the VAE decoder receives this

27
00:01:55,200 --> 00:01:58,666
out of distribution extreme latent values

28
00:01:59,633 --> 00:02:03,600
it cannot reconstruct the normal image stably

29
00:02:04,333 --> 00:02:08,000
and then conduct local output saturation

30
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:10,766
or abnormal highlight values

31
00:02:11,866 --> 00:02:13,200
In the final image

32
00:02:13,200 --> 00:02:16,000
these abnormal values

33
00:02:16,033 --> 00:02:22,100
will appear as a few bright spots

34
00:02:22,233 --> 00:02:26,033
or pixels that are off-color pixels

35
00:02:27,566 --> 00:02:31,600
known as spurious bright pixels or impulse noise

36
00:02:31,966 --> 00:02:34,300
These artifacts not only appear in

37
00:02:34,333 --> 00:02:38,166
dark or high contrast

38
00:02:38,200 --> 00:02:41,266
or high contrast areas

39
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:46,633
but usually are observed in these areas

40
00:02:46,633 --> 00:02:49,633
due to high bright contrast

41
00:02:51,300 --> 00:02:54,666
Because these artifacts usually
come from

42
00:02:54,700 --> 00:02:57,600
a few abnormal latents

43
00:02:58,400 --> 00:03:02,300
it usually has only 1 to 5 pixel size

44
00:03:02,333 --> 00:03:03,866
in a 1k image

45
00:03:04,766 --> 00:03:07,766
Next I will introduce three related solutions

46
00:03:08,800 --> 00:03:11,800
Repaint represents diffusion model patching

47
00:03:12,466 --> 00:03:16,733
PatchMatch represents block texture synthesis

48
00:03:16,733 --> 00:03:21,266
and the Telea FMM represents boundary diffusion

49
00:03:22,466 --> 00:03:24,833
The first method is Repaint

50
00:03:25,166 --> 00:03:27,966
Its core mechanism is to use a mask

51
00:03:27,966 --> 00:03:31,000
to divide the image to be repaired

52
00:03:31,033 --> 00:03:33,800
into known regions and unknown regions

53
00:03:34,766 --> 00:03:36,733
During the denoising process

54
00:03:36,733 --> 00:03:38,366
for known regions

55
00:03:38,400 --> 00:03:44,366
the original image is directly supplemented
with noise at the corresponding time step

56
00:03:45,000 --> 00:03:47,700
Unknown regions undergo normal denoising

57
00:03:48,633 --> 00:03:53,366
The two are stitched together
after this denoising step

58
00:03:54,266 --> 00:03:56,633
To ensure a natural stitch

59
00:03:56,666 --> 00:04:01,133
the image is resampled to the previous step

60
00:04:01,133 --> 00:04:03,900
and denoised again after stitching

61
00:04:04,633 --> 00:04:05,500
Furthermore

62
00:04:05,533 --> 00:04:08,233
to allow the model to more effectively

63
00:04:08,233 --> 00:04:12,633
integrate semantic information
through the denoising process

64
00:04:13,200 --> 00:04:16,666
Repaint introduces the concept of jump lengths

65
00:04:17,466 --> 00:04:24,000
By repeatedly performing forward and reverse
operations across multiple time steps

66
00:04:25,033 --> 00:04:30,800
it improves the harmony and semantic
plausibility of the final image

67
00:04:31,500 --> 00:04:33,833
While this is a powerful method

68
00:04:34,333 --> 00:04:37,700
I believe it is not suitable for the
current situation

69
00:04:39,066 --> 00:04:43,266
Running 250 to 1000 diffusion steps

70
00:04:43,300 --> 00:04:46,066
for a 1 to 5 pixel defect

71
00:04:46,900 --> 00:04:50,533
requiring 8 to 12 GB of GPU memory

72
00:04:50,533 --> 00:04:59,333
and with latency in the seconds
to minutes range is not worthwhile

73
00:05:00,266 --> 00:05:04,133
The second method we will be looking at
today is PatchMatch

74
00:05:05,366 --> 00:05:06,266
To begin

75
00:05:06,300 --> 00:05:09,733
the algorithm covers the target area

76
00:05:09,766 --> 00:05:12,066
the region we want to inpaint

77
00:05:12,066 --> 00:05:14,933
using a sliding window to extract patches

78
00:05:14,966 --> 00:05:17,766
of a specified size

79
00:05:18,866 --> 00:05:20,000
Initially

80
00:05:20,000 --> 00:05:23,633
these patches are randomly paired with patches

81
00:05:23,633 --> 00:05:25,266
of the exact same size

82
00:05:25,266 --> 00:05:27,666
from the available source image

83
00:05:28,466 --> 00:05:33,333
Next we enter the iterative
optimization phase

84
00:05:33,366 --> 00:05:36,233
which is the core of this algorithm

85
00:05:36,233 --> 00:05:39,766
This phase consists of two alternating steps

86
00:05:41,266 --> 00:05:42,700
First propagation

87
00:05:43,133 --> 00:05:47,600
For every patch in the target area

88
00:05:47,700 --> 00:05:53,100
the algorithm checks the matching
results of its immediate neighbors

89
00:05:53,600 --> 00:05:57,566
If a neighbor's offset provides a better match

90
00:05:57,566 --> 00:06:03,000
meaning the source patch it points to
is more similar

91
00:06:03,100 --> 00:06:07,700
the current patch simply adopts
or copies that neighbor's offset

92
00:06:09,133 --> 00:06:11,066
Second random search

93
00:06:11,633 --> 00:06:17,000
Taking the currently matched patch's
location in the source image

94
00:06:17,200 --> 00:06:18,500
as a center point

95
00:06:19,066 --> 00:06:24,233
the algorithm performs random sampling
within a specified radius

96
00:06:24,233 --> 00:06:27,266
This search radius gradually shrinks

97
00:06:27,266 --> 00:06:33,166
allowing the algorithm to fine-tune
and find the best local optimum

98
00:06:35,700 --> 00:06:41,300
These two steps propagation and random search
are continuously repeated

99
00:06:42,000 --> 00:06:45,166
The loop stops either when it reaches

100
00:06:45,166 --> 00:06:48,733
a predefined maximum number of iterations

101
00:06:49,500 --> 00:06:54,466
or when it fully converges meaning the
matching results stop changing

102
00:06:58,800 --> 00:06:59,933
Ultimately

103
00:06:59,966 --> 00:07:04,566
this iterative process generates
a complete look-up table

104
00:07:04,566 --> 00:07:08,133
mapping every single patch in the target area

105
00:07:08,133 --> 00:07:11,533
to its best matching patch in the source image

106
00:07:12,366 --> 00:07:15,200
Now for the final reconstruction

107
00:07:15,200 --> 00:07:17,466
Because the sliding window overlaps

108
00:07:17,466 --> 00:07:23,933
each individual pixel in the target area
will have multiple patches overlapping it

109
00:07:24,166 --> 00:07:26,033
To resolve this

110
00:07:26,066 --> 00:07:28,933
the algorithm uses a voting mechanism

111
00:07:28,933 --> 00:07:35,166
It looks at the corresponding pixels from all
the matched source patches and essentially votes

112
00:07:35,166 --> 00:07:38,666
or averages them out to determine

113
00:07:38,666 --> 00:07:43,033
the most appropriate final color for the
specified pixel

114
00:07:45,133 --> 00:07:47,333
To summarize its application

115
00:07:47,933 --> 00:07:52,766
this method is incredibly well suited
for large

116
00:07:52,866 --> 00:07:56,333
scale object removal and complex
texture reconstruction

117
00:07:56,866 --> 00:07:58,133
Moreover

118
00:07:58,133 --> 00:08:03,766
its speed is significantly faster compared
to the previous method we discussed

119
00:08:05,233 --> 00:08:06,100
However

120
00:08:06,100 --> 00:08:08,200
as I mentioned earlier

121
00:08:08,200 --> 00:08:12,466
PatchMatch is primarily designed for
large-area inpainting

122
00:08:13,266 --> 00:08:16,200
If we are only trying to fix minor

123
00:08:16,233 --> 00:08:18,733
microscopic blemishes

124
00:08:19,100 --> 00:08:22,466
running a full-image search using this method

125
00:08:22,900 --> 00:08:29,166
is not only a waste of computational resources
but it also risks

126
00:08:29,166 --> 00:08:34,700
pulling in irrelevant textures from other
parts of the image

127
00:08:36,733 --> 00:08:40,100
The third method is the Telea FMM

128
00:08:40,833 --> 00:08:42,033
First the algorithm

129
00:08:42,033 --> 00:08:49,133
divides the image into three regions based
on the mask provided by the user

130
00:08:49,133 --> 00:08:50,800
The gray known region

131
00:08:51,166 --> 00:08:52,866
the white unknown region

132
00:08:53,233 --> 00:08:56,900
and the red boundary separating the two regions

133
00:08:58,166 --> 00:09:07,466
Next the algorithm traces along the boundary
to find the outermost ring of pixels inside the hole

134
00:09:08,433 --> 00:09:14,233
This is called band 0 and it is the
very first area to be inpainted

135
00:09:15,633 --> 00:09:17,433
Starting from band 0

136
00:09:17,433 --> 00:09:22,266
the algorithm traverses inward visiting each pixel

137
00:09:22,300 --> 00:09:25,966
and recording its corresponding arrival time

138
00:09:27,000 --> 00:09:31,766
This time serves as a reference for
the inpainting sequence

139
00:09:32,433 --> 00:09:35,700
After calculating the order of every pixel

140
00:09:36,133 --> 00:09:42,400
the inpainting process begins from band 0
which has the earliest arrival time

141
00:09:43,966 --> 00:09:44,933
Theoretically

142
00:09:44,966 --> 00:09:47,833
every time a pixel is inpainted

143
00:09:48,333 --> 00:09:50,466
its neighbors' arrival times are updated

144
00:09:50,900 --> 00:09:56,400
and the pixel with the next earliest
arrival time is chosen for the next round

145
00:09:56,866 --> 00:10:00,233
In actual implementation however

146
00:10:00,233 --> 00:10:02,933
the algorithm first computes the arrival
times for all pixels

147
00:10:02,966 --> 00:10:07,200
and then carries out the inpainting sequentially

148
00:10:07,500 --> 00:10:10,866
For a target point p to be inpainted

149
00:10:11,266 --> 00:10:19,233
the algorithm looks at all known neighboring
points q within a specified radius

150
00:10:19,233 --> 00:10:20,500
For each neighbor q

151
00:10:20,533 --> 00:10:23,966
it uses a first-order approximation

152
00:10:23,966 --> 00:10:27,966
to estimate what color point p should be

153
00:10:28,266 --> 00:10:30,766
as if extending from q to p

154
00:10:31,500 --> 00:10:34,766
Then a weight is calculated based on
three factors

155
00:10:35,300 --> 00:10:37,300
the direction from q to p

156
00:10:37,333 --> 00:10:43,600
the geometric distance and the level set
corresponding to the arrival time

157
00:10:44,700 --> 00:10:50,800
Once the color predictions and weights
from all points q are calculated

158
00:10:51,166 --> 00:10:54,866
they are combined using a weighted average

159
00:10:54,866 --> 00:10:58,066
to get the final color to fill into point p

160
00:10:59,466 --> 00:11:03,133
When all pixels are inpainted in this
calculated order

161
00:11:03,766 --> 00:11:06,433
we get the fully restored image

162
00:11:07,366 --> 00:11:11,666
Because this algorithm doesn't search
through the entire image

163
00:11:11,700 --> 00:11:18,233
but instead only looks at the pixels
near the hole and fills it in what using surrounding colors

164
00:11:18,733 --> 00:11:22,800
it is very fast and highly suitable for
filling small gaps

165
00:11:23,300 --> 00:11:27,833
This makes it a perfect fit for the problem
we are trying to solve right now

166
00:11:28,700 --> 00:11:31,733
Next I would like to introduce my project

167
00:11:32,866 --> 00:11:36,433
The system workflow is broken down
into three main steps

168
00:11:37,566 --> 00:11:41,200
First we identify candidate pixels using
a combination

169
00:11:41,200 --> 00:11:44,900
of the Laplace operator and median residual

170
00:11:45,700 --> 00:11:48,866
utilizing brightness as our threshold

171
00:11:48,866 --> 00:11:52,633
to eliminate false positives and obtain
a highly precise mask

172
00:11:53,400 --> 00:11:59,933
We then filter the results through connected
component analysis and variance filtering

173
00:12:00,533 --> 00:12:01,233
Second

174
00:12:01,233 --> 00:12:06,233
the precise mask is passed to the
Telea FMM method

175
00:12:06,233 --> 00:12:08,100
for the actual image inpainting

176
00:12:08,366 --> 00:12:09,066
Third

177
00:12:09,066 --> 00:12:13,633
we provide a graphical user interface
featuring a red mask preview

178
00:12:14,233 --> 00:12:17,433
This allows for real-time parameter adjustments

179
00:12:17,433 --> 00:12:23,066
and even gives users the ability to manually
edit the mask themselves

180
00:12:23,533 --> 00:12:24,500
However

181
00:12:24,533 --> 00:12:28,400
developing this system comes with a few
key challenges

182
00:12:28,400 --> 00:12:31,566
The first challenge is legitimate

183
00:12:31,733 --> 00:12:34,000
bright details and actual artifacts

184
00:12:34,033 --> 00:12:36,900
can sometimes look nearly identical

185
00:12:36,900 --> 00:12:41,066
making them extremely difficult to
distinguish from one another

186
00:12:41,600 --> 00:12:43,300
The second challenge is that

187
00:12:43,766 --> 00:12:48,500
noise doesn't always manifest as a highly
prominent bright spot

188
00:12:48,600 --> 00:12:53,366
Sometimes it appears as subtle
solid-color blobs

189
00:12:53,366 --> 00:12:58,266
that just look like out of place compared
to their surroundings

190
00:12:58,266 --> 00:13:03,100
And the third challenge is thin, long natural structures

191
00:13:03,166 --> 00:13:06,900
such as strands of hair or fine lines

192
00:13:06,900 --> 00:13:10,666
possess extremely high local contrast
and sharpness

193
00:13:11,266 --> 00:13:12,633
Because of this

194
00:13:12,633 --> 00:13:15,733
local gradient detection algorithms can easily

195
00:13:15,766 --> 00:13:21,466
misidentify fragments of these sharp
natural details as isolated noise

196
00:13:22,300 --> 00:13:24,166
That concludes my presentation

197
00:13:24,566 --> 00:13:25,900
Thank you for listening

